  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div xml:id="AN133.1-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">piriviṭai yāṟṟā ḷāyiṉāḷeṉak kavaṉṟa tōḻikkut talaimaka ḷāṟṟuvaleṉpatupaṭac colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What SHE said to the confidante who was anxious SHE would not have the strength 
            in the time on separation in order to say that SHE had the strength.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN133.1">
            <lg type="edition">
                <l>kuṉṟi yaṉṉa kaṇṇa kurūumayirp</l>
                <l>puṉṟāḷ veḷḷeli mōvā yēṟṟai</l>
                <l>cemparaṉ murampiṟ citarnta pūḻi</l>
                <l>naṉṉāḷ vēṅkaivī naṉkaṉam varippak</l>
                <l>kārtalai maṇanta paimputaṟ puṟaviṉ</l>
                <l>villeṟi pañciyi ṉiḷamaḻai tavaḻuṅ</l>
                <l>kollai yitaiya kuṟumpoṟai maruṅkiṟ</l>
                <l>kariparan taṉṉa kāyāñ cemma<supplied>lō</supplied></l>
                <l>ṭeriparan taṉṉa vilamalar viraiip</l>
                <l>pūṅkaluḻ cumanta tīmpuṉa<supplied>ṟ</supplied> kāṉyāṟṟu</l>
                <l>vāṉkō lelvaḷai <supplied>tīra</supplied> vuṇku</l>
                <l>memmoṭu varutal vallaiyō maṟṟeṉak</l>
                <l>koṉṉoṉṟu viṉaviṉar maṉṉē tōḻi</l>
                <l>yitaṉmuḷ ḷoppiṉ mukaimutir veṭci</l>
                <l>kolpuṉak kuruntoṭu kallaṟait tāvu</l>
                <l><supplied>mī</supplied>rnāṭ ṭatta<supplied>t tīrñcuvaṟ</supplied> kalitta</l>
                <l>varimaraṟ kaṟikku maṭappiṇait</l>
                <l>tirimarup piralaiya kāṭiṟan tōrē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>“By the side of the small mound in the dry-land field in the clearing, (7)</l>
                <l>where young clouds, like cotton cast with a bow(?), cast over</l>
                <l>the woodland of intertwined fresh bushes in the rainy season, (5f.)</l>
                <l>while the bearded male white rat with puny legs,</l>
                <l>lustrous fur [and] eyes like Kuṉṟi [seeds]</l>
                <l>lines up a good thick [layer] of good, day[-fresh] kino blossoms</l>
                <l>in the dust scattered from mounds of red pebble, (1-4)</l>
                <l>by the forest river with sweet floods that are turbid [and] laden with flowers,</l>
                <l>mixing the blossoms of the silkcotton tree, like fire spreading,</l>
                <l>with the faded blooms of the ironwood tree, like charcoal spreading (8-10)</l>
                <l>we would finally eat, [you with] pure, beautiful, bright bangles. (11)</l>
                <l>Are you strong [enough] to come with us?”, (12)</l>
                <l>[this] one thing he asked [us], friend, (13)</l>
                <l>– the one who has gone to traverse the wilderness of the Iralai [deer] with twisted horns, (18)</l>
                <l>with youthful does that chew striped bowstring hemp</l>
                <l>grown on the wet hillocks by the roads through the wet land, (16f.)</l>
                <l>where the Veṭci with mature buds similar to the thorny [claws] of the partridge</l>
                <l>spreads on the stony rocks along with the wild lime by the [freshly] cleared fields. (14f.)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
